"font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">eview</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">and approved </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">appointment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">f the Chief Constable and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Deputy Police and Crime Commissioner</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 102.21pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Panel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provided a public forum for the nominated officer to answer questions and explain his approach on a variety of topics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and, in that respect, we feel the process was useful for the public of West Yorkshire.  Over and above th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e Panel verify</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that the PCC had followed a thorough process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, it is less clear how the Panel’s veto may have been used usefully given the stringent limits on who can be nominated as Chief Constable.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 102.21pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Panel’s opinion is that its role i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s less valuable with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> regards </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">appointment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Deputy PCC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  The legislation is clear that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">role of the Deputy PCC is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to be shaped wholly by the PCC, with no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">specific </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">requirements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  As </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such, the Panel felt unable to add greatly to the process and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">note</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with sympathy the point made by PCC Mark Burns-Williamson that he would have preferred to stand alongside a named Deputy PCC in the election. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul></ul></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 85.05pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Considered and approved </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">policing precept</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 102.21pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Panel feels this is a crucial role as it allows for the PCC to set out and justify </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his budget and precept proposal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Through th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is, the Panel was able to agree with the PCC a number of conditions for its approval of the precept, including limiting costs of the PCC’s office; that recruitment of new officers should reflect the diversity of the force</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> area and further information BE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provided on PFI projects.  This made the process more transparent for residents and, through on-going monitoring, has helped local partners to use resources more effectively.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul></ul></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 120.5pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 85.05pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Provided for the PCC to present and answer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> questions on his Annual Report</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 102.21pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Annual Report for 2012/13, presented in November 2013, was limited.  The circumstance for this was acknowledged and, although the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">value of Panel’s scrutiny on this was very limited, we believe it is likely to be a worthwhile task in future years.   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul></ul></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 85.05pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Convened two Sub-Panels to consider complaints matters</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 102.21pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Panel feels that it has been unable to add value to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">complaints process.  Where complaints are serious (that is, of a criminal nature), they are referred to the IPCC.  Where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">complaints are not serious and informal resolution can be sought local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly, our experience is that the likelihood</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of a satisfactory outcome being reached for the complainant and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PCC is very slim (as previous resolutions will have been unsuccessful</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">result</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the complainant turning to the Panel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The investigation and attempted resolution of complaints consumes a significant amount of time and resource</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ul></ul></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the legislation also provides </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scope for panels to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“review or scrutinise decisions made, or othe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">r action taken, by the relevant Police and Crime C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ommissioner in connec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">tion with the discharge of the C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ommissioner’s functions”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We feel this is important for three reasons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as it pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ovides for the opportunity for P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">anels to add greatest value to the governance of policing and crime reduction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:4pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:4pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 85.05pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In provides for Panels to play important roles in ensuring that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">strategic direction of all partners relates to common goals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> expressed in the Police and Crime Plan.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  This rests on the Panel’s work on local policing priorities and its links to Community Safety Partnerships and local Scrutiny Committees, as explained in more detail in section 3 below.  In addition, however, the Panel has also been greatly encouraged by how the PCC and other partners, including from local criminal justice agencies, have shown a commitment to work together to deliver the Police and Crime Plan. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 85.05pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Panel is able </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">support the PCC make the strategic links</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with local authorities.  In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">practice, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Panel Chair briefs Council Leader</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s on significant issues in order that they are aware of contextual information, and any concerns or views the Panel has, so that Leaders’ work with the PCC is as constructive and informed as possible. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 85.05pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Police and Crime Commissioner for West Yorkshire has a total budget </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of approaching £2bn during a full</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> term of office.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where major policy positions are decided upon, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Panel can ask the PCC to explain why </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a decision was taken</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and what the expected implications might be.  Although currently the Panel has been disappointed that the online record of the PCC’s decisions has been regularly out-of-date, we look forward to this being rectified in future in the interests of public accountability. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 85.05pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A good example of this discretionary work in action was the PCC’s response to a critical report by HMIC in July 2013.  The Panel took the initiative to meet with HMIC Inspectors to fully understand the context and future implications of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">work.  In responding to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">report, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he Police and Crime Commissioner has assured the Panel that, in his reviews with the Chief Constable, he will seek improvement plans in respect of not only burglary but rape, serious sexual assaults and other areas where West Yorkshire is at the low end n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ationally amongst</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> its group of similar forces.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Well-informed scrutiny and support is crucial.  Therefore, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he Panel has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">been very pleased at the Police and Crime Commissioner’s strong and proactive stance in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">raising with the Home Secretary and Office for National Statistics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> concerns about the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">restrictions on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">publish</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> timely information on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">crime trends and comparative </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">performance.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Currently, the Panel and PCC are only able to use comparative data that is between three</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and six </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">months</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> old.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he Panel feels frustrated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that it is not able</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to give the public of West</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Yorkshire the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> up-to-date position</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and we would urge the Committee to support the collective work of the Panel and PCC for West Yorkshire to broker a better approach nationally. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of commissioners in promo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ting local policing priorities</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Panel has excellent links with local Community Safety Partnerships and Crime and Disorder Scrutiny Committees.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These relationship are underpinned by Principles of Engagement and, in a practical sense, local partners provide a quarterly ‘Local Perspective’.  This highlights areas where the PCC is working well with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> local partners and has provided real evidence that they and the PCC have regard to each other’s priorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In a very practical sense, the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Panel has raised important issues on the PCC’s approach to commissioning and supported his pass</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">porting of funding for community safety and crime prevention work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> until October 2014</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> On behalf of partners, the Panel has urged the PCC to share, and consult on his emerging commissioning framework for activity beyond October 2014, at the earliest possible opportunity. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is through the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Local Perspectives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> process that the Panel has noted and supported the PCC on the significant commitment he has shown to get out and engage with community groups, partners and residents across West Yorkshire.  The Panel feels this is crucial for him to be able to understand and promote local policing priorities. </span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Panel has also supported the PCC in his commitment to refresh the Police and Crime Plan for West Yorkshire, underpinned by a major </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘Listening to You’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consultation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">exercise. </span></p><p style="font-size:7pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An annual meeting of the Panel with CSP and Scrutiny Committee chairs also allows partners to identify where learning can be shared and joint or coordinated work undertaken.  Following the meeting in July 2013, CSPs have shared information and approaches on common issues including a pilot Restorative Justice project in Bradford and approaches to tackling d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">omestic violence in Leeds.  Similarly, the Scrutiny Committees agreed to undertake a coordinated exercise about the roles of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and local authority contribution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> PCSOs in West Yorkshire.  All of these measures have helped provide decision-makers at the appropriate level with better information about how they can help deliver the outcomes in the Police and Crime Plan. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The role of commissioner</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s in budget and precept setting</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Police and Crime Commissioner has over £400m per year to spend on making people in West Yorkshire safer and feeling safer.  The majority of this is delegated to West Yorkshire Police and under the control of the Chief Constable, with the remainder spent on community safety projects that help prevent crime, support victims and achieve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the other priorities within</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Police and Crime Plan.</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Panel’s role is to scrutinise and support the Police and Crime Commissioner’s decisions about the use of resources in West Yorkshire.  Over the last 12 months, we have:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 4pt 48.76pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Examined the Police and Crime Commissioner’s decision to raise the policing precept on Council Tax by £5 for a Band D property.  This provided more clarity about what the extra money would be sp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ent on and the Panel has ensured</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that the 44 extra Police Officers have been recruited;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 4pt 48.76pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Helped the Police and Crime Commissioner to explain to partners and residents how Government decisions have affected the resources available for policing in West Yorkshire over the next four years;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 4pt 48.76pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Recognised the considerable achievement in West Yorkshire of already delivering £65m of savings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in 2010/11 and 2011/12</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> - the majority of which were from reductions in the pay bill for Police officers and staff; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 4pt 48.76pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Worked with the Police and Crime Commissioner to ensure his Office costs are subject to the same financial constraints placed on the Force as a whole – saving £213,000</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> p.a. by 2016/17</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 4pt 48.76pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Challenged the Police and Crime Commissioner to make collaborative procurement – particularly in conjunction with other forces in the region - more effective; and, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Liaised with the Audit Committee to confirm the Police and Crime Commissioner’s financial controls are strong and that residents can have confidence in them. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The role of commissioners in holding t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">heir chief constable to account</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:6pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It’s good news that crime in West Yorkshire is falling and the Panel recognises the vital role played by those who work in our local communities to make them safer.  The Panel feels it would be helpful for residents to have clearer milestones and contextual information to allow them to reach their own judgements about the Police and Crime Commissioner’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">progress.</span></p><p style="font-size:6pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The PCC holds fortnightly Community Outcome meetings with the Chief Constable, which is the principal route by which he is held to account.  The Panel understands its role to be to ask the PCC to explain how he has ensured that the Chief Constable is ensuring the outcomes in the Police and Crime Plan are achieved.  This includes priorities the PCC has identified alongside the Chief Constable to focus on; the evidence that has been used to identify those priorities and what tangible improvements the PCC and Chief Constable expect to see. </span></p><p style="font-size:6pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Panel also seeks to understand how the PCC and Chief Constable respond to financial information about the Force’s Programme of Change and its overarching budgetary position. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Again, the Panel looks to triangulate information from meetings with evidence from the OPCC or external partners like HMIC.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Progress on establishing collaboration agreements with other commissioners, poli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">cing organisations and partners</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As Forces across Yorkshire and the Humber move to a new model of regional collaboration through a ‘lead force’ model rather than a collective resource, the Panel will look for evidence that the PCC is holding the Chief Constable to account for those areas where West Yorkshire leads, and to make sure that local residents are being well-served on issues that are led by colleagues elsewhere. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Police and Crime Panel has made contact with other Panels across Yorkshire and the Humber to explore the appetite for sharing le</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ssons and information about the collaborative activities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Collaborative arrangements with other local partners such as local authorities have been discussed in other sections.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The division of functions and staff between commissioners and chief constables following the Stage 2 transfers under the Police Reform and S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ocial Responsibility Act 2011</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Panel has taken interest in the division of functions and staff through the Stage 2 transfer.  Keen to undertake as much of its work as possible in public, the Panel was keen to look into the agreed Stage 2 process at its meeting on 13</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> December.  However, to our knowledge the Home Office’s response to the local proposal was not received within the indicated timeframe of the end of November. </span></p><p style="font-size:7pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Panel remains keen to look into the agreed position in a public setting at the earliest opportunity.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Transparency of and repo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rting by commissioners to date</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:7pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Panel has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a Memorandum of Understanding with the PCC on the sharing of information and respective roles on detailed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">processe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s like complaints.   After one year of operation, this is un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">der review based on the experience</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the last 12 months</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and will also take the opportunity to clarify the nature, quantity and format of information required by the Panel to enable it to exercise its role effectively</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Broadly, the Panel is pleased with the PCC’s commitment to place information onto his website that is not classified as Restricted.  Whilst further work is needed for this to always be up-to-date, we are confident that learning and better working practices after the Stage 2 transfer will help. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The Panel feels that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by the PCC publishing a clear forward plan and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> more up-to-date information</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the Panel’s scrutiny and support role might become even more effective.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Panel would also reiterate to the Committee the transparency and reporting issues it raised in point 2.4 about the inability to use comparative </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iQuanta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> information in a timely manner. </span></p><p style="font-size:6pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Councillor Alison Lowe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Chair,</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">West Yorkshire Police and Crime Panel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> s.28(6a) of the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011</span></p></body></html>